[14:56:34] zc-trickster says: Myelination is the primary neuroscience analogy for instinct training, as it refers to the process of forming a myelin sheath around neurons to increase the speed of signal transmission, mirroring how repeated practice and training can automate and accelerate instinctual responses. Synaptic pruning also plays a role, as it eliminates unnecessary neural connections, refining the efficiency of instinctual pathways. Both processes work in tandem to solidify instinctual behaviors.
